# foundation board registry override (foundation #770) — EXAMPLE, not read.
#
# Only a file literally named `boards.conf` (no `.example`) is consulted, at
# one of two locations, in this order (first hit wins):
#   1. machine-level: $XDG_CONFIG_HOME/foundation/boards.conf
#      (default ~/.config/foundation/boards.conf)
#   2. repo-local override: workflows/scripts/board/boards.conf (next to this
#      file)
# If NEITHER exists, board.sh / funnel-tick.sh / funnel-drive.sh fall back to
# their own built-in case maps (this repo's own real values — see those
# files' own comments) — so a consuming repo (e.g. one that gets a synced
# copy of board.sh but never a conf file) behaves identically to today.
#
# Format: one `board.<N>.<axis>=<value>` per line. axis is one of:
#   repo     "<owner>/<name>"  — repo-owner axis (gh issue create -R, REST)
#   owner    "<login>"         — project-owner axis (gh project ... --owner)
#   project  "<number>"        — project-number axis (gh project <number> ...)
#   backend  "issues"          — tracker backend axis (foundation #799).
#                                 Default (omitted, or any other value) is
#                                 "projects" — the Projects-v2 path unchanged
#                                 from before this axis existed. Set to
#                                 "issues" to run that board with NO Projects
#                                 board at all: item CRUD + Status ride plain
#                                 `fnd:`-namespaced GitHub labels instead (see
#                                 workflows/scripts/board/ISSUES-ONLY-BACKEND.md
#                                 for the full label vocabulary). An
#                                 issues-only board only needs the `repo` axis
#                                 — `owner`/`project` are meaningless without a
#                                 Projects board and are simply never read.
#   cache    "on"               — issue-plane read-cache enable axis
#                                 (F#988/#1026, cache-read-dispatch item's
#                                 Contract; workflows/scripts/board/lib/cache.sh
#                                 + its sibling CACHE-STORE.md). install/doctor
#                                 provision and report the on-disk store for
#                                 ANY board with a `cache=` line, regardless of
#                                 backend — but the read-dispatch short-circuit
#                                 itself only fires TODAY for a `backend=issues`
#                                 board; it has no effect yet on a
#                                 `backend=projects` (or unconfigured) board,
#                                 which never reads this store. Default
#                                 (omitted, or any other value) is OFF — the
#                                 whole-board issues-only read stays the live
#                                 `gh issue list` call it always was. Set to
#                                 "on" to instead serve that read from
#                                 lib/cache.sh's on-disk issue-cache store (a
#                                 durable, cross-session, per-repo snapshot of
#                                 the full issue corpus) — but ONLY takes
#                                 effect if the calling process has ALSO
#                                 sourced lib/cache.sh; if it hasn't, board.sh
#                                 falls back to the live read with one stderr
#                                 notice (fail-safe, never a silent behavior
#                                 change). See ISSUES-ONLY-BACKEND.md § Read
#                                 cache staleness bound for more. This axis
#                                 only ENABLES the mechanism; it is never
#                                 written by `make install`/`make doctor` —
#                                 they only ever PRINT the opt-in line for a
#                                 board that lacks one, same human-owned-
#                                 conf-file discipline as `backend`. Tuning the
#                                 store itself (root directory, max-stale
#                                 window) is deliberately ENV VARS, NOT a
#                                 boards.conf axis — see `CACHE_STORE_ROOT` /
#                                 `CACHE_STORE_TTL` in cache.sh's own header
#                                 for the knobs and their defaults.
# These are deliberately SEPARATE axes (#330) — do not collapse them.
# Blank lines and lines starting with # are ignored. This file is parsed with
# grep/cut only — never sourced or eval'd — so it cannot execute code.
#
# The values below are a PLACEHOLDER example — replace with your own org/repo
# registry. Board numbers are logical (arbitrary, chosen by you); onboard a
# new board by adding its 2-3 lines here (or by extending the built-in case
# maps directly if you're maintaining a fork rather than overriding).

board.1.repo=acme/widget-app
board.1.owner=acme
board.1.project=1
# Opted into the issue-cache store — install/doctor provision the on-disk
# store for board 1 regardless of backend; the read-dispatch short-circuit
# itself only fires today for a `backend=issues` board (see the `cache`
# axis comment above):
board.1.cache=on

board.2.repo=acme/internal-tools
board.2.owner=acme
board.2.project=2

# An issues-only board (no Projects-v2 board provisioned) — just the repo axis:
board.3.repo=acme/kernel
board.3.backend=issues

# An issues-only board that also opts its whole-board read into the on-disk
# issue-cache store (only takes effect for a caller that has sourced
# lib/cache.sh — see the `cache` axis comment above):
board.4.repo=acme/kernel-warm
board.4.backend=issues
board.4.cache=on
